<br>
Be that as it may, and despite the recent change, I believe that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Double Bolts</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are appropriate, balanced, and should be restored to the game.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> BACKGROUND:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Although the exact mechanics behind it are not clear, prior to recent UI patch, it was possible for casters to sometimes get a bolt spell to strike its target twice, resulting in both double damage and double aggro.  This capability has been in the game for at least three years, and seems most likely due to a combination of game geometry and client/server lag.  The UI patch removed this <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;bug,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and specifically apologized for mages for doing so.<br>
<br>
My argument is simple.  First, bolts already suffer from a number of limitations that do not apply to other damage spells, that make them less reliable.  Second, it requires both skill and opportunity to take advantage of it.  Third, it entails additional risk, since both strikes cause aggro.  All in all, I and doubtless others find it balanced in terms of risk versus reward.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Like a bolt of out the blue:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Bolt spells require an uninterrupted line of sight from the caster to the target, otherwise they do not strike.  Unfortunately, almost anything can block line of sight, from unseen bumps in an apparently smooth flat surface, to, it seems, invisible fart clouds floating through space.  The apparent 3-D image rendered on our screens is often quite different from the actual game geometry, and a clear line of sight can be difficult to obtain.  In my experience, the frustration of missing even a single bolt because of an invisible or inobvious obstactle keeps these spells tucked away in my spell book.  Up to a point, the additional damage gained by double bolts is more than offset by the damage lost when bolts miss because they are blocked by seen or unseen obstacles.<br>
<br>
The slightly improved damage to mana ratios of bolts over shocks does not balance the inherent weaknesses of bolt spells.  However, the possibility of double bolts might well.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> He was the best shooter west of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> High Pass</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  In order to get a double bolt requires both significant skill and knowledge of the terrain, as well as the proper terrain.  The mage must position both themselves and the enemy, and keep both positioned.  Since the double bolt causes double aggro, keeping an enemy fixed is no mean feat.  Hardly any magicians have mastered these skills, and they are rightly proud of their demonstration of knowledge and discipline.  With the capacity in the game for three years, these few mages had every right to expect it remain within their ability.  Unlike the development team, these <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sharp Shooter Magi</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> know exactly the difficulties and risks involved in using this skill.  In contrast, the development team has examined one simple aspect of the spell, the damage to mana ratio, and concluded, naively, that it is unbalanced, despite no evidence in game that any mages where rising inappropriately in level, or defeated foes that should be properly beyond their means.  Instead, the developers appear to have <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>assumed</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> that it must be a problem, when in fact, it is not.<br>
<br>
By removing this reasonable and balanced capability after three years with no problems or complaints, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has knowingly spat on some of the most dedicated, experienced and observant <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in the game, whose only <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;crime&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was to use the spells granted them to the best of their ability.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Moster Love:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Not only do double bolts require a great deal of additional effort and skill to obtain, they also involve additional risk due to increased aggro.  The two bolts hit in quick succession, and both count for the full aggro of the spell.  This means if root breaks or does not stick, the likely result is that the enemy will seek to do unspeakable things to a mage whose only physical protection may be a silk nightgown and an ice cream cone.  At the very least, this movement will change the geometry and may well mean the enemy may be blocked from even single bolts.  In the new relative position, even a single missed bolt neatly compensates for the previous double bolt that caused him to move.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Boltsploitation:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s one undeniable possible concern would be if double bolts could always be reliably reproduced in a given geometry.  That is, if there were spots that the mob could be held in place, and the mage could stand were they always or nearly always got double bolts, then it would be a clear exploit, equivalent to fear kiting an enemy into a dead end.<br>
<br>
While this is a legitimate concern, there are ways to fix this that would preserve double bolts, and the pride and enjoyment of those that have mastered the skill.  To give just one possibility, the mage's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Thrown Weapon</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> skill could be used to determine if a double bolt struck, and might even be used to avoid minor obstacles in the path.  Those who use double bolts would quickly build their skill.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Conclusion:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  As long as they are not completely reliable and require skill and opportunity, double bolts are fair and balanced and should be restored, albeit with some modifications to avoid abuse.  Bolts spells are inherently tricky to use in the first place, and missed bolts compensate for double bolts.  They have been in the game for over three years, and have become a mark of distinction for some of the most dedicated and observant mages, who, as customers, deserve better treatment than a wholesale clipping of a point of pride.<br>
<br>
THEREFORE, we petition for the return of double bolts.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Master ArchMage Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Ancient Fellowship, Xev</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
